t in Nikolai Lebedev’s Remake The Crew (2016) -- t11 Mistaken Identities: Millennial Remakes, Post-Socialist Transformation and Hungarian Popular Cinema -- t12 Refashioning the Remake: A Bigger Splash -- tPart IV Industrial Perspectives: Practices of Production and Circulation -- t13 Remake and Decline in Scottish Cinema: Whisky Galore! 1949 and 2016 -- t14 ‘Remakable’ Directors: The Contemporary Spanish Media Industry and Popular Discourses on Remakes and National Authorship -- t15 Remakes and Globally-Oriented European Cinema: Contemporary Industrial Practices and Shifting Hierarchies -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCombines historical and contemporary approaches to film remakes in EuropeInvestigates, next to the textual, socio-cultural and political dimensions, the often neglected industrial, financial and production-related dynamics of European remake practicesProvides a mix of different methodologies, ranging from comparative textual analysis to production, promotion, and reception analysisTakes into account both popular and art cinema remakesExamines European film remakes within local, regional, national, transnational or transcultural contextsOffers new theoretical concepts and methodological models that take into account both the distinctive and universal aspects of film remaking in a European contextBringing together a range of international scholars, European Film Remakes discusses for the first time the textual, socio-cultural, political, and industrial mechanisms and singularities of the film remake in a European context. Offering a variety of historical, theoretical, and methodological approaches, the book is illustrated by a wide range of case studies from across Europe, including films like A Bigger Splash, Open Your Eyes and Perfect Strangers. Although commonly understood as a typical Hollywood practice, this book demonstrates how film remakes are, and always have been, a significant part of the European film culture and industry.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh1 aAraüna Baró, Núria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuelenaere, Eduard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForrest, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoye, Stijn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aJoye, Stijn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeitch, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMathilde Frank, Stefanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeir, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMunro, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoordenbos, Boris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSanyal, Kamalika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSlugan, Mario, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Iain Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSouch, Irina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStewart, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVan Heuckelom, Kris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVarga, Balázs, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVerevis, Constantine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVerstraten, Peter, econtribut